1
00:00:00,571 --> 00:00:26,393
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhasam Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhasam Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhasam

2
00:00:26,727 --> 00:00:31,135
homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:33,476 --> 00:00:42,107
Last time we tackled this nama-rupa, the body-mind complex.

4
00:00:42,128 --> 00:00:44,090
And we said something about ayatana, I think.

5
00:00:44,670 --> 00:00:52,860
So I just want to do the next three links, because that completes the part of the dependent origination that we don't actually have control of.

6
00:00:52,920 --> 00:00:54,203
It's automatic.

7
00:00:55,003 --> 00:01:01,392
Once you've got a body and mind, you have these senses, and there are six senses.

8
00:01:02,384 --> 00:01:05,105
So there's the five that we know of and the mind itself.

9
00:01:05,667 --> 00:01:10,792
When Buddhism talks about the mind itself, it uses a special word, mana.

10
00:01:12,293 --> 00:01:26,004
And it's really talking about that bit where whatever stimuli are coming in through the senses, somehow it's being put on a screen and it's being collected.

11
00:01:26,805 --> 00:01:31,530
But it also refers to the stuff that comes up in the mind itself as memory and emotion.

12
00:01:31,965 --> 00:01:45,802
So the idea is that the senses themselves have not only a base on the retina, and we know also in the brain, but also in the mind itself, which is separate from the brain.

13
00:01:48,186 --> 00:01:56,876
And this word āyātana is a sphere, so you can't have one sphere interrupting with another.

14
00:01:57,042 --> 00:01:59,004
So you can't hear through your eyes.

15
00:01:59,566 --> 00:02:05,055
Now I know there's such a thing as synesthesia where people smell numbers and stuff like that.

16
00:02:06,057 --> 00:02:08,762
But that's happening elsewhere.

17
00:02:08,822 --> 00:02:14,951
Actually on the sense base you can only see through the eye, full stop.

18
00:02:14,972 --> 00:02:20,822
And this word āyātina is a sphere of experience.

19
00:02:21,814 --> 00:02:29,163
So people who are blind simply don't have the sphere of experience of colours and sights, you see.

20
00:02:29,182 --> 00:02:36,370
And it's an important word because when he's describing Nibbāna, just as an aside, he uses the word āyatana.

21
00:02:36,770 --> 00:02:40,213
It's a sphere, a sphere of experience.

22
00:02:41,556 --> 00:02:44,318
And they talk about the inner and outer.

23
00:02:44,579 --> 00:02:47,502
So the outer part is the actual object.

24
00:02:48,932 --> 00:02:53,240
And the inner part is the sense base.

25
00:02:53,699 --> 00:02:59,308
So there's an object and a sense base which, as you know, arise on the retina or at the eardrum.

26
00:03:01,412 --> 00:03:04,195
But it's still based upon the object from outside.

27
00:03:05,016 --> 00:03:10,786
So, in this sense, Theravada is a sort of qualified realism.

28
00:03:11,888 --> 00:03:16,054
It doesn't deny that things outside us exist.

29
00:03:17,265 --> 00:03:26,236
But what it says is we can only know what we know through our physical and psychological processes.

30
00:03:27,479 --> 00:03:37,311
So it's a sort of, you could almost call it a qualified idealism as well, that all you can know is what your consciousness knows, and it can only know what it receives through the senses.

31
00:03:38,712 --> 00:03:43,138
So you can't know things in themselves, you can only know the attributes of something.

32
00:03:47,826 --> 00:03:50,932
And that's quoted straight from the Majjhima Nikaya.

33
00:03:51,153 --> 00:03:56,745
Each of the five faculties owns a different sphere and none of them partake of the spheres of another.

34
00:03:58,007 --> 00:03:59,850
And they have mind as their support.

35
00:04:01,875 --> 00:04:03,337
Without the mind, the ideal is easy.

36
00:04:03,598 --> 00:04:04,300
Simple as that.

37
00:04:05,544 --> 00:04:10,531
So then we have this next step on dependent origination which is the contact.

38
00:04:11,432 --> 00:04:16,619
So this is the point, the Buddha here is describing the point where we come to know something.

39
00:04:16,899 --> 00:04:23,889
So the body and mind and the five senses are the instruments with which the contact is made.

40
00:04:24,428 --> 00:04:27,233
And for this contact to happen there has to be an object.

41
00:04:27,449 --> 00:04:31,036
It has to be a sense base and there has to be consciousness.

42
00:04:31,057 --> 00:04:42,740
Now this consciousness, this vijnana, remember is the same consciousness that we get in the five khandhas, the five heaps, which is that basic act of cognition.

43
00:04:42,721 --> 00:05:04,036
right and it's obviously a very complex thing because it not only picks up say of this chair it not only picks up the colors and the shape of the chair but it also understands what it is the chair so there's other things going on in the mind which eventually lets you know that a chair is there and it's to be sat upon

44
00:05:04,016 --> 00:05:06,507
And that's all part of that process.

45
00:05:06,930 --> 00:05:13,420
But it begins at a very simple base of the photons hitting the eye.

46
00:05:15,391 --> 00:05:40,302
and when they talk about that when the scriptures talk about that at the actual five sense basis that's where the mind contacts matter and it only knows it it would seem in these four ways fire earth water fire and wind I always get the sequence wrong so earth is you know the sense of pressure

47
00:05:40,535 --> 00:06:05,935
of weight things like that water is congealing magnetism it's what draws together it's what keeps it's what keeps you know it's what turns wheat into dough it's that sort of you know sometimes in the breath you can feel it you see you feel like an elasticity and that's the that's the water element

48
00:06:07,314 --> 00:06:12,862
Fire is heat, of course, and here remember that photons would be considered a fire element.

49
00:06:14,144 --> 00:06:15,084
And wind is movement.

50
00:06:15,766 --> 00:06:26,079
So picking up on those qualities, the mind then forms a concrete picture in the mind of what it is.

51
00:06:26,718 --> 00:06:28,521
So we know that, don't we?

52
00:06:29,583 --> 00:06:33,507
It's amazing how all that's happening at the eardrum is this tapping.

53
00:06:34,432 --> 00:06:39,680
It really is, it's just a tapping and yet it's taken in and it turns into a sound.

54
00:06:40,500 --> 00:06:41,302
It's quite remarkable.

55
00:06:45,105 --> 00:06:56,661
And then when we get that, I should have also mentioned that of course when it comes to emotions, that's a physical contact.

56
00:06:57,096 --> 00:07:02,310
Emotions manifest in the body as feelings, as this contact.

57
00:07:03,012 --> 00:07:10,290
And at some point there's a definition of what we're experiencing as either pleasant, unpleasant or neutral.

58
00:07:10,651 --> 00:07:12,877
At that point it becomes Vedana feeling.

59
00:07:13,651 --> 00:07:23,247
So what Veda is, is a perception of the hedonistic value of what you're experiencing, whether it's pleasant, unpleasant or neutral.

60
00:07:23,947 --> 00:07:32,382
So it doesn't change what you're actually experiencing, it's just your perception of it, an internal decision as to whether it's pleasant or unpleasant.

61
00:07:32,983 --> 00:07:36,790
And you can't stop living in that dualistic world.

62
00:07:36,887 --> 00:07:41,033
So the world is always going to be experienced either as pleasant or unpleasant.

63
00:07:41,053 --> 00:07:50,910
And even when we say neutral, when you really go into the neutral, the neutral feelings, you find it splits one way or the other into pleasant and unpleasant.

64
00:07:51,610 --> 00:07:53,213
So you can't go beyond that.

65
00:07:53,653 --> 00:07:55,216
That is given.

66
00:07:55,557 --> 00:07:56,377
You see, that's a given.

67
00:07:58,560 --> 00:08:03,468
And it gives it a feeling coloration to what we're actually experiencing.

68
00:08:04,732 --> 00:08:09,238
So let's take for instance in the sitting you might get pain in the knee.

69
00:08:10,961 --> 00:08:14,887
As that sensation comes into consciousness we begin to realise it's pain.

70
00:08:16,129 --> 00:08:20,735
So pain is a feeling that we are now experiencing as unpleasant.

71
00:08:20,795 --> 00:08:21,997
It's an unpleasant feeling.

72
00:08:23,377 --> 00:08:31,293
Now forgetting the next stage, which is usually a reaction or resistance to it, let's just go straight into it, supposing it's not a pain that you have any problem with.

73
00:08:31,733 --> 00:08:46,821
So now as you bury your attention into the pain, it's as though you flip, it's as though you go from a barrier of whether it's likeable or unlikable into just pure feeling, pure sensation.

74
00:08:46,801 --> 00:08:56,634
And at this point, you begin to experience pain as sensation and you can deconstruct it.

75
00:08:56,714 --> 00:09:00,097
You can say, oh, there's a bit of pressure there, there's a bit of heat there.

76
00:09:00,339 --> 00:09:05,985
And at that point, your attention, your consciousness has come right slap bang up against matter.

77
00:09:07,548 --> 00:09:07,628
See?

78
00:09:08,975 --> 00:09:11,379
And in your meditation, you can play around with that.

79
00:09:11,779 --> 00:09:17,311
You can, at one minute, perceive it as pressure, as pressure and heat.

80
00:09:17,812 --> 00:09:22,461
And next minute, by just pulling back off, you can see this clicking in as pain.

81
00:09:23,605 --> 00:09:27,129
And just to be able to play around with that sometimes.

82
00:09:27,671 --> 00:09:28,572
Like an itch.

83
00:09:28,591 --> 00:09:35,523
See, an itch is a sort of funny thing because it's neither pleasant nor pleasant unless you scratch it.

84
00:09:35,543 --> 00:09:44,735
But as you go into it, it's quite, it's sort of, you know, you go beyond the idea of an itch into these very sharp little pointy sensations.

85
00:09:44,716 --> 00:10:06,386
So, remember that the whole idea of splitting up our, or of experiencing our, what we experience in this way, in this sort of deconstructed way, is to undermine the idea that this is a self, that this is some body.

86
00:10:06,366 --> 00:10:11,356
And what we begin to realize is it's just this process that happens in time.

87
00:10:12,077 --> 00:10:14,863
And once it's perceived and gone, that's it.

88
00:10:14,883 --> 00:10:15,283
It's finished.

89
00:10:15,303 --> 00:10:16,485
The process begins again.

90
00:10:17,087 --> 00:10:17,908
And there's nobody there.

91
00:10:17,948 --> 00:10:22,017
You don't need somebody to create pain in the knee.

92
00:10:22,057 --> 00:10:24,662
You can just bang it on a chair and the pain will arise.

93
00:10:26,025 --> 00:10:34,436
And pleasant feelings arise, unpleasant feelings arise, in meditation especially, and you haven't called for them, they just arise themselves.

94
00:10:35,136 --> 00:10:47,292
And it's that sense of not being in control, you see, of these things that mirror back to us that maybe this isn't me, not me, not mine.

95
00:10:54,881 --> 00:11:00,030
So that brings us really to the point of dependent origination, which is a given.

96
00:11:02,335 --> 00:11:09,988
And that's also, remember, when we say it's a given, it's also something which is the product of the past.

97
00:11:11,437 --> 00:11:13,940
It's a product of what's happened in the past.

98
00:11:13,960 --> 00:11:16,763
So there's your karma coming in in this present moment.

99
00:11:17,244 --> 00:11:24,873
So at the beginning of any sequence of experience, there's always a given, but that's dependent upon your karma.

100
00:11:26,315 --> 00:11:33,023
Now, not entirely dependent, because as you know, your eye base, the retina, is dependent on your genetics.

101
00:11:33,604 --> 00:11:39,029
You can't say that's my personal karma, because that's been brought up through generations.

102
00:11:39,009 --> 00:11:42,144
If you haven't got good eyesight like me, you're just stuck with it.

103
00:11:42,988 --> 00:11:46,725
That's not because in the past life I was poking somebody's eyes out.

104
00:11:48,932 --> 00:11:51,735
So this whole thing becomes quite complicated.

105
00:11:51,816 --> 00:11:56,879
But in a sense, to complicate it is sometimes to miss the point.

106
00:11:57,561 --> 00:12:04,005
Because what liberates us is seeing these three characteristics.

107
00:12:04,025 --> 00:12:07,669
So when we see the impermanence of it, we see it as a process.

108
00:12:08,309 --> 00:12:17,057
And when we see it as not me, not mine, because we're distanced from it, because it's become an object of attention, that's what liberates us.

109
00:12:17,077 --> 00:12:18,078
That's what liberates us.

110
00:12:22,666 --> 00:12:25,932
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

111
00:12:25,951 --> 00:12:37,552
May you be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

